Analyzing Racial Hate Crimes from 2013 to 2019¶

by Jiawei Wang and JiYuan Cao

The COVID-19 pandemic might be one of the most influencial pandemic in the modern history. As of May 11 2021, there are more than 158 million confirmed cases and 3.29 million deaths attributed to COVID-19. And it led to the largest global recession since the Great Depression. Numerous lifes had already suffered from this pandemic, but some people vehemently related those tragities with Chinese and Asian who encountered the first outbreak of COVID-19 and suffered because of it. This thought led to an increased amount of racism acts that against Asians and Asian Americans and caused more innocent people to suffer in this difficult time period.

In 2020, the Center for the Study of Hate and Extremism at California State University reported that the Anti-Asian hate crimes had increased by 150%. And the Stop AAPI Hate organization had received 3,795 Asian-hate incidents from March 19, 2020 to February 28, 2021. And here is their report: https://secureservercdn.net/104.238.69.231/a1w.90d.myftpupload.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/210312-Stop-AAPI-Hate-National-Report-.pdf .

More Info about 'hate crimes' against Asian Americans: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-56218684

As a respond to the ongoing Stop Asian Hate activism, our group members, who are part of the Asian and the anti-racism community, felt the responsibility to act against racism and introduce Asian's current situation to more people in our society. Thus, in our final tutorial project, we would like to introduce the process of data science and analyze historical (racial) hate crimes in the US with slightly more focus on Anti-Asian hate crimes.

The Data Science pipline has the following 5 phases:

  1. Data collection
  2. Data Manegement/Representation
  3. Exploratory data analysis
  4. Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning
  5. Communication of insights

And we will go throught those 5 phases in our tutorial project by analyzing racial hate crimes in the U.S. from 2013 to 2019.

1. Data collection:¶

I believe you already know that data is the most fundamental thing of data science. It's the base of all the fancy data science techniques. Also, we want the data source to be reliable because only real data can reflect reality and provide meaningful insights. So first, let's collect our data.

We collected our data from the FBI Hate Crime database( which is reputable) by downloading their excel packages from year 2013 to 2019. We selected this time range because Anti-Asian incidents were first seperated from other race biased incidents in 2013, and the latest year in FBI's hate crime database is 2019. Here is FBI's website for hate crime data : https://ucr.fbi.gov/hate-crime

Then we transfered downloaded excel files to the google drive for remote accessibility and collaboration.

P.S. Eventhough this time range didn't provide us many information about Anti-Asian hate crimes after COVID-19, we can still analyze historical patterns of race related hate crimes in this time range. And those patterns can provide us a useful background information when we learned about numbers of Anti-Asian hate crimes in 2020 or 2021 from reports or media afterwards.

2. Data Management/Representation¶

After the data collection, we are still one step away from analyzing it. The Data Management/Representation phase is a big part in the real-life data science since we can't directly use collected data in most cases. Data may contain missing values or irrelavent information, and we don't want those data to interfere our analysis focuses. After selecting useful data, we need to put those data into containers that we can directly use in our future analysis.

The FBI already cleaned the data for us which means there are no missing values in the "real" part of tables to deal with. And it's a good news for us.

But since the FBI Hate Crime excel files are seperated by years (there are 7 files in differnt format) and containing hate crimes other than race-bias incidents, we can't use them directly.

First, we need to extract race related statistics from each table.

And then, we need to aggregate those statistics from 2013 to 2019's files into one table so that we can use it to see the historical pattern in future analysis.

Taking table of 2019 as example, we see that the data we need for race-related bias is from row 6 to row 16, but since years before 2015 only has races from row 6 to row 13, we 'll choose row 6-13 for our data analysis. Those rows contain Anti-white, Anti-Black, Anti-American Indian, Anti-Asian, Anti-Native Hawaiian and Anti-Multiple Races bias motivations.

How do you think about the graph above? Do you think it fairly reflected how each race experience discrimination in our society because it was plotted based on each race's incidents / total incidents ? If your answer is yes, then you've fallen into our trap HAHAHA! Look into the Normalization part.

Normalization

If we want to compare racial hate crimes across races, then normalization can undermine the population related bias in previous data.

From U.S. Census Burearu's Website(https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/US/PST045219), we learned about the population construction in the U.S.

And we found that each race has different percentage in the whole U.S. population.

" White alone, percent 76.3%

Black or African American alone, percent 13.4%

American Indian and Alaska Native alone, percent 1.3%

Asian alone, percent 5.9%

Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander alone, percent 0.2%

Two or More Races, percent 2.8%"(from U.S. Census Burearu)

Thus, race with bigger population may have more people to be the victim, which results a higher incident number even they have a less likelihood to be attacked. And smaller population race may have less incidents just because they have less people to be the victim, while each individual is more likely to encounter hate crimes in life.

For example, suppose the total population is constituted by 1000 people in Race A and 10 people in Race B, we found out that each individual in Race A has 1% probability to be a victim of racial hate crime and individuals in Race B have 90% probability to be a victim. And in the report of race hate crime incidents, we would probabily see 19 racial hate crime incidents. 10 of them are from Race A, and 9 of them are from Race B. If we take the percentage of each race's hate crime incidents in the total incidents, we would have 53% for Race A and 47% for Race B. And we may incorrectly conclude that those two race are approximately equal likly to encounter racial hate crimes. But in fact, individuals in Race B are 90 times more likely to be victims of racial hate crimes in this society.

Taking the differences in population percentage in to consideration, we would like to normalize our data, which is setting all races to the same population and then comparing their normalized racial hate crime incidents.

Using the example above, if we want to normalize the racial hate crime incidents in that population, we need to find the ratio between 2 race's population and then multply this ratio to the hate crime incident numbers to the desired group. We see that Race A has a population 100 time larger than Race B, so if we multiply 100 to Race B's population, we will have a imagined Race B who have the same population as Race A. And we can do the same thing to racial hate crime incident number, which would normalize it too. And the incident number would be 900 in this case. To put it in English, we would say if Race B has the same polulation as Race A, then we would expect 900 racial hate crime incidents in the hate crime report. And now we see the 900 racial hate crimes to Race B is 90 times larger than the 10 racial hate crimes to Race A, which preserved the difference between each indicidual's likelyhood of encountering racial hate crimes in two races.

Now, we will aplly normalization to our data and treat white people as the Race A in the previous example. And use the population statistics from U.S. Census Burearu to perform the normalization on each race.

# select needed part from Bias_data

print(ratio)

# multiply ratios to the corresponding race
Bias_data_Normalized =  Bias_data_Normalized.mul(ratio,axis = 0)

Analysis based on previous two graphs (Incidents & Percentage):

From this graph we can see that African Americans in the U.S. are indeed most likely to experience discrimination comparing to other races( except for 2017) which is consistent with our conception of racial problems in our society. It's interesting to notice that in year 2017, there is a significant drop in the percentage of hate crimes for African American people, but in the incident graph, the incidents actually increased in 2017 for black people. This percentage's drop was because of the surge of Anti-American Indian incidents in 2017, not because of less discriminations agianst African American people.

And for the American Indians or Native Americans, we can see that before 2017, they are only less likely to experience discrimination than black people both in the percentage and incidents graph. But in 2017, there is a surge in the racial hate incidents against Native Americans. And we believe this is relevant to the Dakota Access Pipeline event (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dakota_Access_Pipeline_protests). But after 2017, we see that the percentage and incidents both dropped for Native Americans, which might attribute to the #NoDAPL (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NODAPL) movement.

For Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander, we are very sad to see the percentage and incidents both increased a lot over time. In 2013, both incident and percentage were lower than Anti-Asian hate crimes and slightly more than Anti-White hate crimes, but in 2019, both of them are higher than all races other than African Americans. And our group didn't anticipate this result. Even though we don't know the reason behind this shocking increase of Anti- Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander incidents, we do feel the need of more investivations in the future and the need of support for the Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander group.

Other three races looks more "steady" in 2013-2019.

The Multiple race group expericened a gradual increase in incidents in 2013-2017, and the incidents remained at that level in 2018-2019.

The Asian Americians are only more likely to experience discrimination than white people from 2015-2019. And there is a slightly increase in incidents after 2016. And our observation is also consistent with the "middle class white" image for Asians in our society. But from our current knowledge, we know it's very likely to have a "surge" in Anti-Asian hate crimes in 2020-2021. And we can see how fragile this "middle class white" image is when there comes a disturbing factor and how difficult it is to eliminate racism.

The white people, as we expected, are least likely to experience discimination. It has the lowest percentage and incidents from 2013-2019.

Now if you look at the previous 'wrong' graph, you can tell how "misleading" it is if you want the comparison across all races.

4. Machine learning and Hypothesis testing¶

After analyzed our data, we are equipped with much more understandings about our data. Now let's move to phase 4: machine learning and hypothesis testing. This part can be the most powerful part in data science. We can build models based on current data and use this to make predictions. And we can also test our hypothesis. It can validate our assumptions or answer our questions about our data.

Machine learning

Import needed modules for regression

We will primarily utilize sklearn and its linear regression model as our major tool for Machine Learning. scikit-learn(sklearn) is an open source mahine learning tool based in Python. It provides simple and efficient tools for predictive data analysis.

In this case, we are using its linear regression model, because our dataset is mostly linear. Year is the only numerical sources among all dependencies in our dataset.

We will first make a linear regression model using sklearn, then we can use it to predict the trend of each race's incidents number from 2020 to 2026. In [ ]:
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [16,9]

for x in range(0,6):# for each race

  y = np.array([2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019]).reshape(-1, 1)
  z = np.array(Bias_data_Normalized.iloc[x,1:])# get each row
  model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
  model = model.fit(y,z)  # doing the linear regression
  predict = np.array([2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019,2020,2021,2022,2023,2024,2025,2026]).reshape(-1, 1) # years to plot

  race = Bias_data_Normalized.at[x,'Bias'] # get race
  plt.scatter(marker = "x", x = y, y = z, label=str(race)) # scatter each year's incident
  plt.plot(predict, model.predict(predict), label="regression for " + str(race)) # plot the regression line
  
plt.title(" Regression (based on historical data) to predict future normalized hate crime incidents")
plt.xlabel("Years")
plt.ylabel("Incidents")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

From the plot above, we can come up with a thesis: all kinds of racial incidents are increasing. The only differences is their rate of increase. The racial discrimination against Black people are increasing at a much lower rate comparing to the incidents commited against Native people of America: Indians, Hawaiians and other Pacific Islanders. The Black Lives Matter movements in recent years have made some achievements to support the Black community.

And for Asian Americans, we see the regression line is slowly increasing. But from 2021's perspective, we don't think our regression line predicted the surge of Anti-Asian crime incidents in 2020. And this reveals a disadvantage of our model. Our model predicts future incidents by historical data(incidents). It means that, assuming everything is approximately the same as before, this is what we think will happen in the future. But in reality, future is always unpredictable, just like no one foreseen the arrival of COVID-19.

In the machine learning, we see that every race seems to have a increasing trend of experiencing discrimination. But in part three, we see that the incidents are not always increasing for every race in 2013-2019. And this lead us to question: Does racial hate crime incidents increased overtime?

Hypothesis Testing (Is incident number increasing over time?)

Now lets make a hypothesis and test it out. First, we have to understanding the definiton of hypothesis testing. Hypothesis testing is a statistical method of determination if your created model is a good fit or not. As the name indicates, a null hypothesis and an alternative hypothesis would be included in a hypothesis testing. We want to set up the hypothesis in such a way that the null hypothesis can be rejected and the hypothesis can be proven true. A significance level(alpha) is the other important indicator for machine learning. If the p value of the random variables is within the significance level, aka the rejection level, the null hypothesis is then rejected.

In our case of racial incidents, we will be looking at the relation between year and total amount of racial incidents. We are looking forward to an linear relation between these two numerical data. Since both of these variables are numerical and related directly without medians, we will be using the linear regression model in statsmodel as the tool to indicate whether therer exists a linearity between the years and the incident numberss.

H0: there is no linearity between the years and the incident numbers

Ha: there is a linearity between the years and the incident numbers

significance level: 0.05

Importing module for hypothesis testing.

Since this module needs at least 8 samples to calculate p-values, we choose to do a regression about incidents in the recent ten years.

From this regression line and our p-value test, we are very sad to see that the racial hate crimes do increases overtime.

But do you remember the disadvantage of our prediction model? It can only predict the future incidents ASSUMING everthing is the same as the past. Eventhough there are possibility that we will met incidents, like COVID-19, that will increase racial hate crimes in our society, it is also possible that the movement and the education of racial equality will gradually change our slope from positive to negative!
